Below is a **single, self‑contained C‑compatible header+implementation** that you can drop straight into the BlockSci source tree (or ship as a pre‑built library).  

It

* hides the C++ BlockSci iterator behind an opaque `blocksci_iter_t`,
* gives C callers a tiny `blocksci_block_t` view of each block,
* lets the caller pass a **callback** that is executed for every block,
* lets the callback stop the walk early,
* propagates C++ exceptions as integer error codes,
* is deliberately lightweight – the hot path (the loop that calls the callback) is a plain `for`‑loop with no virtual calls, no heap allocation and no lock‑contention.

```c
/* ==== blocksci_c.h – public C API =================================================
 *
 *  Copyright (c) 2026  YourCompany / BlockSci contributors
 *  SPDX‑License-Identifier: MIT
 *
 *  This file is deliberately a *single* translation unit: the header part is
 *  guarded by `#ifdef __cplusplus` and the implementation follows it.
 *
 *  It provides a C‑friendly way to walk the whole blockchain (≈800 M blocks)
 *  while letting the user supply a per‑block callback written in plain C.
 *
 *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  QUICK START (C):
 *
 *      #include "blocksci_c.h"
 *
 *      static int my_cb(const blocksci_block_t *blk, void *ud) {
 *          // Example: count blocks whose timestamp is after 2024‑01‑01
 *          uint64_t limit = *(uint64_t*)ud;
 *          if (blk->timestamp > limit) ++(*(size_t*)ud);
 *          return 0;                     // 0 → keep iterating
 *      }
 *
 *      int main(void) {
 *          blocksci_iter_t *it = NULL;
 *          if (blocksci_iter_new("/path/to/blocksci/db", &it) != 0) return 1;
 *
 *          uint64_t ts_limit = 1704067200ULL;   // 2024‑01‑01 00:00:00 UTC
 *          size_t count = 0;
 *
 *          int rc = blocksci_iterate(it, my_cb, &ts_limit);
 *          if (rc < 0)   fprintf(stderr, "iteration error %d\n", rc);
 *
 *          blocksci_iter_free(it);
 *          printf("blocks after 2024‑01‑01: %zu\n", count);
 *          return 0;
 *      }
 *
 *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  THREAD‑SAFETY
 *
 *      * Each `blocksci_iter_t` instance is **not** thread‑safe – do not call its
 *        functions from multiple threads simultaneously.
 *      * Different iterator objects can be used concurrently.
 *
 *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  ERROR CODES
 *
 *      0   – success (full walk completed)
 *     -1   – generic failure (e.g. out‑of‑memory)
 *     -2   – user‑callback asked to stop early (not an error)
 *     -3   – C++ exception thrown while opening the DB
 *     -4   – C++ exception thrown while iterating
 *
 *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 */

#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

#include <stddef.h>   /* size_t */
#include <stdint.h>   /* uint*_t */
#include <stdbool.h>  /* bool */

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Opaque iterator handle – allocated by blocksci_iter_new() and freed by
 *  blocksci_iter_free().
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct blocksci_iter_s blocksci_iter_t;

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Minimal block view exposed to C.  The fields are deliberately POD so the
 *  callback can read them without any extra indirection.
 *
 *  * height      – block height (0 = genesis)
 *  * timestamp   – Unix epoch seconds (UTC)
 *  * hash        – pointer to a 32‑byte block hash (big‑endian)
 *  * hash_len    – always 32
 *
 *  The pointer is valid only for the duration of the callback call; if the
 *  caller needs to keep it longer they must copy the bytes.
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct {
    uint32_t   height;
    uint64_t   timestamp;
    const uint8_t *hash;      /* 32‑byte SHA‑256 block hash */
    size_t     hash_len;      /* == 32 */
} blocksci_block_t;

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Callback prototype.
 *
 *  Return 0 to continue iterating, any non‑zero value to abort the walk.
 *  The `user_data` pointer is passed unchanged from the call to
 *  `blocksci_iterate()`.
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*blocksci_block_cb)(const blocksci_block_t *blk, void *user_data);

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Public API (C linkage)
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/**
 * @brief Open a BlockSci database and create an iterator over its blocks.
 *
 * @param db_path   Path to the BlockSci DB directory (UTF‑8, NUL‑terminated).
 * @param out_iter  On success receives a pointer to a newly allocated iterator.
 *
 * @return 0 on success, negative error code on failure.
 *
 * The iterator must be released with `blocksci_iter_free()`.
 */
int blocksci_iter_new(const char *db_path, blocksci_iter_t **out_iter);

/**
 * @brief Release an iterator created by `blocksci_iter_new()`.
 *
 * @param it  Iterator to free.  Passing NULL is a no‑op.
 */
void blocksci_iter_free(blocksci_iter_t *it);

/**
 * @brief Walk the whole blockchain, invoking `cb` for each block.
 *
 * @param it          Iterator (must be non‑NULL and not yet exhausted).
 * @param cb          User supplied callback – must not be NULL.
 * @param user_data   Opaque pointer passed to each callback invocation.
 *
 * @return  0  – walk completed normally (all blocks visited)
 *         -2 – callback returned non‑zero, walk stopped early (not an error)
 *         -4 – internal C++ exception while iterating (fatal)
 *
 * The iterator becomes exhausted after the call, regardless of the return
 * value.  To walk again the caller must create a fresh iterator.
 */
int blocksci_iterate(blocksci_iter_t *it,
                     blocksci_block_cb cb,
                     void *user_data);

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  End of public C API
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#endif /* BLOCKSCI_C_H */

/* ============================================================================
 *  Implementation – C++ side (compiled as C++ but exposed with C linkage)
 * ============================================================================ */
#ifdef __cplusplus
/* --------------------------------------------------------------
 *  The implementation is compiled as C++ (requires a C++ compiler).
 *  It pulls in the real BlockSci headers, builds a thin wrapper,
 *  and then exposes C functions with `extern "C"`.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include <exception>
#include <new>          // std::bad_alloc
#include <cstring>      // memcpy
#include <memory>       // std::unique_ptr
#include <vector>

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Replace the following includes with the actual BlockSci headers
 *  that provide:
 *    - class Block (or similar) exposing height, timestamp, hash()
 *    - class BlockIterator (or similar) supporting ++ and * operators
 * ----------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include "blocksci/blocksci.hpp"   // <-- adjust to real header name

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Minimal wrapper around the real BlockSci iterator.
 *
 *  The wrapper owns the BlockSci DB object (so that the iterator stays
 *  valid) and keeps the iterator itself.  All state lives on the heap,
 *  but the hot loop only dereferences a raw pointer – no virtual calls.
 * ----------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct blocksci_iter_s {
    // The real BlockSci objects are kept inside a unique_ptr to avoid
    // accidental copying.
    std::unique_ptr<blocksci::Chain> chain;      // owns the DB
    blocksci::Chain::iterator   it;              // iterator over blocks
    blocksci::Chain::iterator   end;             // end sentinel
    bool                         exhausted = false;
};

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Helper: translate a BlockSci block into the C struct.
 * ----------------------------------------------------------------- */
static inline void fill_c_block(const blocksci::Block &bs_block,
                                blocksci_block_t *c_block)
{
    c_block->height    = static_cast<uint32_t>(bs_block.height());
    c_block->timestamp = static_cast<uint64_t>(bs_block.timestamp());
    c_block->hash_len  = 32;
    c_block->hash      = reinterpret_cast<const uint8_t*>(bs_block.hash().data());
}

/* -----------------------------------------------------------------
 *  C‑linkage wrappers
 * ----------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" {

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Open DB and create iterator.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
int blocksci_iter_new(const char *db_path, blocksci_iter_t **out_iter)
{
    if (!db_path || !out_iter) return -1;
    try {
        // Allocate the opaque struct
        blocksci_iter_t *wrapper = new blocksci_iter_t();

        // The real BlockSci API: `Chain` is the high‑level object that
        // gives us an iterator over blocks.
        wrapper->chain = std::make_unique<blocksci::Chain>(db_path);
        wrapper->it    = wrapper->chain->begin();
        wrapper->end   = wrapper->chain->end();
        wrapper->exhausted = false;

        *out_iter = wrapper;
        return 0;
    } catch (const std::bad_alloc &) {
        return -1;                     // out‑of‑memory
    } catch (const std::exception &) {
        return -3;                     // DB opening threw
    } catch (...) {
        return -1;
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Release iterator.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
void blocksci_iter_free(blocksci_iter_t *it)
{
    delete it;   // safe even if it is nullptr
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Walk the whole chain, invoking the user callback.
 * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
int blocksci_iterate(blocksci_iter_t *it,
                     blocksci_block_cb cb,
                     void *user_data)
{
    if (!it || !cb) return -1;
    if (it->exhausted) return -1;          // already used

    try {
        // The hot loop – no heap allocation, no virtual call.
        for (; it->it != it->end; ++it->it) {
            const blocksci::Block &bs_block = *it->it;

            // Build the C view on the stack (fast).
            blocksci_block_t c_block;
            fill_c_block(bs_block, &c_block);

            // Call user code.  Any non‑zero return aborts the walk.
            int cb_ret = cb(&c_block, user_data);
            if (cb_ret != 0) {
                it->exhausted = true;
                return -2;                  // early stop requested
            }
        }
        it->exhausted = true;
        return 0;                           // normal completion
    } catch (const std::exception &) {
        it->exhausted = true;
        return -4;                          // iteration threw
    } catch (...) {
        it->exhausted = true;
        return -4;
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
 *  End of extern "C"
 * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
}   // extern "C"

#endif /* __cplusplus */

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  End of single‑unit header+implementation.
 * --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens | Why it matters for performance |
|------|--------------|---------------------------------|
| **`blocksci_iter_new`** | Opens the BlockSci DB (`blocksci::Chain`) and stores a `std::unique_ptr` to it. The iterator (`it`) and its end sentinel (`end`) are cached. | Opening the DB is done once; the iterator is cheap to copy (just two pointers). |
| **`blocksci_iterate`** | A tight `for` loop walks `it` → `end`. For each block we fill a small POD struct (`blocksci_block_t`) on the stack and call the user‑supplied C function. | No virtual calls, no allocation, no lock‑contention. The only overhead is the function call itself – exactly what pandas/polars do when they invoke a Python lambda per row. |
| **Early‑stop** | If the callback returns non‑zero we break out and return `-2`. The iterator is marked *exhausted* so the caller cannot reuse it inadvertently. | Mirrors the “break” semantics users expect from high‑level libraries. |
| **Error handling** | All C++ exceptions are caught and turned into negative error codes. The API never throws. | Guarantees a clean C ABI – callers only need to check integer return values. |
| **Thread‑safety** | Each iterator owns its own `Chain` object; multiple iterators can be created in parallel. | Allows a user to run several independent walks in different threads if desired. |

You can now compile this file with a C++ compiler (e.g. `g++ -std=c++17 -fPIC -shared -o libblocksci_c.so blocksci_c.h`) and link it from pure‑C programs. The public header (`#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H … #endif`) is all a C program needs; the implementation part is compiled out of the way.
